# Humans Attack Vectors

## Date Completed

June 2026

## Objective

Understand how attackers exploit human behaviour through phishing, malware, social engineering, deepfakes, and credential theft, and learn how a SOC Analyst can identify and mitigate these threats.

---

## Scenario 1: Malicious Software Download

### Description

A software engineer downloaded a suspicious 7-Zip installer from an untrusted website. The installer was repeatedly blocked by antivirus software.

### Investigation

- Reviewed the source of the downloaded file.
- Identified the website as an untrusted freeware distribution site.
- Determined that the file posed a security risk.
- Chose to quarantine the executable rather than whitelist it.

### Outcome

The executable was identified as a data-stealing malware sample and prevented from executing.

### Skills Practiced

- Malware identification
- Endpoint security
- Threat containment
- Security decision-making

---

## Scenario 2: Phishing Email Investigation

### Description

A finance employee received an email claiming a payment had been processed through Stripe.

### Investigation

- Examined sender domain.
- Identified the domain as fraudulent.
- Reviewed the attached archive file.
- Determined the attachment contained malicious content.

### Indicators of Compromise (IOCs)

| Type | Value |
|--------|---------|
| Suspicious Domain | stripe-payments.xyz |
| Attachment | Invoice.rar |

### Outcome

The phishing email was blocked before execution of malicious content.

### Skills Practiced

- Email analysis
- Phishing detection
- IOC identification
- Threat assessment

---

## Scenario 3: Deepfake CEO Impersonation

### Description

An IT support employee received a phone call from an individual claiming to be the CEO requesting a password reset.

### Investigation

- Reviewed authentication procedures.
- Verified identity through approved channels.
- Determined the request was not legitimate.

### Outcome

A deepfake-based social engineering attempt was prevented.

### Skills Practiced

- Social engineering detection
- Identity verification
- Incident escalation
- Access control procedures

---

## Scenario 4: Anomalous Login Investigation

### Description

A user account generated a login alert from an unusual location.

### Investigation

- Reviewed login activity.
- Examined URLs visited prior to authentication.
- Identified a fake Microsoft login page.
- Confirmed credential theft activity.

### Indicators of Compromise (IOCs)

| Type | Value |
|--------|---------|
| Suspicious URL | login[.]microsoft365-online[.]ru |
| Suspicious URL | hroyhiqtspqgkp[.]info |

### Outcome

The compromised account was identified and protected from further misuse.

### Skills Practiced

- Login anomaly investigation
- URL analysis
- Credential theft detection
- Incident response

---

## Key Lessons Learned

- Human users remain one of the most targeted attack vectors.
- Phishing campaigns often rely on spoofed domains and malicious attachments.
- Deepfake technology can be used to bypass traditional trust mechanisms.
- Suspicious login activity should always be investigated alongside user behaviour and browsing history.
- Security awareness and verification procedures are critical layers of defence.

